# Collections

## What are Collections?

## Collections are complex Data Types. Instead of containing a single value, collections can hold an unlimited amount of other Data Types. They provide a way to concisely hold repetitive data. Values inside of a collection are called members.

Visual:  
![][image2]

# Tuples

## What is a Tuple?

## Tuples are the simplest kind of collection. They hold other data types in a comma separated list enclosed by parentheses. You can not make this collection bigger than it is on creation. You can only redefine members.

Example:  
![][image3]

## Accessing Tuple Members

## You might be wondering, what if I want to access a specific member?

## Of course there’s a way to do that.

## ***But FIRST… Indexes.***

## Indexes

## Indexes are how you access the members of most complex data types. An index is where a member is inside of a collection. Most collections number the place of each piece of data inside of it. However, the count starts at 0\.

## Let’s review the Tuple example but with indexes in mind.

![][image4]

## Or even fancier.

![][image5]

## This is called destructuring and is faster and more concise when you want to create variables from a Tuple’s members.

## Accessing Tuple Members 2.0

## So to be concise…

## You access Tuple members by invoking the name of the variable containing the Tuple followed by a period and the index of the member you want to access.

Example:  
![][image6]

## “n-1” represents the index. “n” being the spot you want and subtracting one to get that values index because the indexes start at 0\.

# Arrays

## What is an Array?

## An Array is a very strict collection. Not only is it not “growable”. You can only have one Data Type. This extends to other collections you might have placed inside.

Example:  
![][image7]

## Accessing Array Members

## Accessing Array members is slightly different from Tuples. You still invoke the name of the variable containing the Array. This time, you place square brackets next to that. Finally, you put the index of the member inside the brackets.

Example:  
![][image8]

# Strings

## Strings? Again?

## Yes, the String data type is actually a collection. Specifically, it’s a collection of characters.

What a String looks like to you:  
![][image9]  
What a String kind of looks like to a computer:  
![][image10]

## Unlike a Tuple, you can make a String bigger than its size on creation. Adding to a String is just putting more characters at the end.

## Slices

## Of course you can access specific parts of a String by indexing, in fact you can (or rather have to) access a range from within a String. This is called a slice, a slice is a string literal created from referencing a part (or all) of a String.

## There is a little bit of a procedure to create a slice.

## First, you need a String variable to reference.

Step 1:  
![][image11]

## Then, you must create a variable to hold the slice.

Step 2:  
![][image12]

## After that, you use the borrow operator (&) followed by the name of the variable we’re referencing.

Step 3:  
![][image13]

## Then, you put square brackets right after the name of the borrowed variable.

Step 4:  
![][image14]

## Finally, you put a range inside the brackets to get which specific characters you want.

Step 5:  
![][image15]

# Vectors

## What is a Vector?

## A Vector is a collection that only allows you to hold a specific kind of data. However, you *can* add more of that data after creating the Vector.

Example:  
![][image16]

## Creating A Vector

## Like all collections, Vectors are complex Data Types. Creating a Vector (& Hashmap) is however a little bit different. To create a vector, easily, you have to use “associated functions”. An associated function, asfun, is a function implemented for a Data Type to make handling and manipulation easier.

## There are several different asfuns you can use to create a vector. They also have different use cases.

## New

## The new function creates an empty Vector. This is the most bare-bones you can be, all you have to do besides using the function is annotating the type. Of course, remember to make the variable mutable.

Example:  
![][image17]

## With Capacity

## The with\_capacity function creates a Vector with a certain size. When you create a Vector with new, the program has to make space for each new entry, which is slower than having that space made on creation. You simply pass with\_capacity the size you expect.

![][image18]

## From

## The from function creates a Vector from an array that you pass to it. It is the closest thing to how you would define a Tuple or an Array. You have to use an array because Array members all have to be the same type, just like a Vector.

Example:  
![][image19]

## Adding New Members

## Vectors can in fact have new members put into them after they are created. This can be done with another asfun called push.

## Asfuns that are used on a Data Type after creation are called the same way you access a member from a Tuple. You place a period after invoking the variable and then put the name of the function.

Step 1:  
![][image20]

## Then, you place parentheses after the function’s name to signify that you’re using it.

Step 2:  
![][image21]

## Finally, you place the new data you want to add to the Vector inside the parentheses. Make sure it is of the same Data Type.

Example:  
![][image22]

# HashMap

## What is a HashMap?

## A HashMap is a unordered collection that binds a key to a value. You use keys to access values. HashMaps are also growable and type specific.

Example:  
![][image23]

## Creating A HashMap

## HashMaps have the same associated functions as Vectors.
